[1]
Date: Mon, 7 Jun 2004 13:57:08 +0100
From: Jillian Deans <Jillian.Deans@hse.gsi.gov.uk>

I have 2 comments to add:
(1) Do we also need to consider the risks from working with
animals in a laboratory setting? These may be deliberately
infected with zoonotic agents or else naturally infected (see
MMWR 36(19) 1987 - Secondary transmission of herpes B).
(2) As regards reporting of laboratory accidents, there is a duty in
the UK [legislation passed in 2000] to report any infection reliably
attributable to work (including that in a laboratory) or any accident
or incident which results in, or could have resulted in, the release
of a Hazard Group 3 or 4 biological agent.
<http://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/hse31.pdf>
<http://www.hse.gov.uk/statistics/causdis/infect.htm>
Those reported infections and incidents that occur in CL3 and CL4
laboratories (equivalent to BSL-3 and BSL-4) are currently
independently investigated by Health and Safety Executive
Specialist Inspectors (of which I am one).
There is also a duty in UK (and EU) legislation to report accidents
involving significant and unintended releases, outside primary
containment, of GMOs [genetically modified organisms. - Mod.JW] -
- see: <http://www.hse.gov.uk/dst/acgm32/paper4.htm>.
Enquirers can make approaches to HSE via our information
helpline <hseinformationservices@natbrit.com> for general
information, as this is held centrally by the HSE Statistical Units.
But I do have direct access to the numbers of incidents (both GM
and non-GM) that have been investigated by the unit that I work for -
- during 2003 we investigated at least 14 laboratory incidents/
accidents (I say at least, because some of the incidents have not
been coded properly) and 2 laboratory-acquired infections. We
also investigated 3 GM accidents (this became a duty in 2000 -- all
reports from Members States are passed to the European
Commission).
Unfortunately, I can't let you have details about the non-GM
incidents, because the information we collect in the course of an
investigation is protected (in part) by the Health and Safety at Work
etc Act 1974 (Section 28) -- we would have to deal with any
requests on a case-by-case basis. However, you may find a
general approach via the infoline (above) sufficient for your
purposes. Information about the GM accidents is kept on a public
register, and you can request this information via our notifications
officer <diane.fox-purday@hse.gsi.gov.uk>.
We have published information on lessons learnt from investigating
such incidents since 2000 which may be of use to ProMED -- see
<http://www.hse.gov.uk/dst/acgm31/paper9.htm> and
<http://www.hse.gov.uk/dst/acgm32/paper8.htm>).
--
Jillian Deans
HM Specialist Inspector of Health and Safety (Biological Agents
Unit)
Health and Safety Executive
Magdalen House
Stanley Precinct
Bootle, Merseyside, UK
<Jillian.Deans@hse.gsi.gov.uk>
