[2]
Date: Mon, 07 Jun 2004 11:24:08 -0400
From: Lewis B. Sckolnick <info@rectorpress.com>

I think the issues Tony Della-Porta raises [see ref. (02) below] are
of most import, but beyond what he has to say is a new system of
political correctness which is overriding laboratory safety and
human health.
We must move to bring laboratories in all parts of the world to the
same standards and not assume that an "Institute" in the former
USSR is modern. I had a chance to visit the medical school at
Semipalatinsk (7 Tents), Kazakhstan, in September 1990. The
training laboratory there was well below what one would expect to
find in a 2nd-rate United States high school, much equipment
having been donated without instruction, and my guide was the
director of the medical school.
The biophysics laboratory at Al Farabi University in Almaty, visited
in March 1991, was also at the high school level but well below
Semipalatinsk -- so much for being the largest university in the
country.
We cannot allow places that lack facilities and trained, intelligent
personnel to carry on.
--
Lewis B. Sckolnick
7 VI 2004
Leverett MA USA
<info@rectorpress.com>
[I would hope things have improved at Russian universities in the
last decade, but have serious doubts. Can someone who has
seen Russian research labs more recently give us an update? -
Mod.JW]
